This formula shows the deep relationship between the complex exponential function and trigonometric functions and is valid for any real number. The great physicist Richard Feynman called the formula "our jewel" and "one of the most remarkable, almost astounding, formulas in all mathematics." It has applications in complex number theory, trigonometry, electrical engineering, differential equations, and so much more.

A line is defined as a linear equation. A line expands infinitely. If you pick any two points on a line, the part of the line between those two points is a line segment. A ray is a line which is finite at one end and infinite at the other. You can think of it as having a staring point but no end point.
A parabola is one of three conic sections. These are sections of a cone that intersects a plane. Parabolas provide a good model for motion of objects like a ball being thrown in the air.

A hyperbola is another one of the three conic sections. Like parabolas, there are many practical uses in fields like astronomy and physics. Open orbits and the study of subatomic particles both rely on hyperbolas.

The last of the three conic sections is the ellipse. Closed orbits follow this path. Aside from planetary orbits, such as the Earth around the sun, in optics an ellipse describes the index of refraction. A circle is a form of an ellipse with both denominators, "a" and "b", in the equation equal to 1.

A super ellipse is used to make asteroids and squircles (square-circles). If n is 1, the the result is a diamond. If n < 1 then the result is an asteroid form. If n > 1 then the result is a squircle. However, if n is 2 the result is a circle.

Triangles can be right (90º) oblique (no internal angle of 90º), obtuse ( one internal angle > 90º) or acute ( all internal angles < 90º). Two triangles are said to be congruent if two sides and the included angle between the two triangles are equal (SAS). Two internal angles and the included side are equal between the two (ASA), all the sides share the same length (SSS) or two internal angles and the non-included side are equal (AAS).
A square is a regular quadrilateral in which all side are at right angles. Because of this all diagonals of a square are perpendicular.
A rectangle is a closed planer quadrilateral with four right angles. A rectangle with all equal sites is a square.
This shape is a quadrilateral with a line of symmetry bisecting a pair of opposite sides. The base angles are congruent as are the diagonals.
A rhombus is a quadrilateral in which all four sides are equal. By this definition a square and rectangle can be considered to but rhombi.
Circles are a simple shape consisting of a set of points in a plane that are all equal distance from a given point, the center. The distance from the center is the radius.

A circular sector is the portion of a circle enclosed by two radii and the arc in between. These equations are good for finding volumes of fluids in a cylinder or understanding some shapes to integrate over.

A circular ring (annulus) is a plane bounded by the circumference of two circles of two different radii. A few examples would be the face of a washer or the face of a pipe. This formula for finding the area of a circular ring holds even when the circles are not concentric.
The basis for computer graphics and many games are convex polygons. Having a good feeling of convex and concave polygons is good if you’re interested in this field.
Concave polygons have at least one internal angle greater than 180º. Any concave polygon can be made into a convex polygon.

Pentagons are 5 sided polygons. The chords of a regular pentagon are in golden ratio to its sides. Like hexagons, they're found all over nature, in plants like apples and morning glories to animals like the sea star.
Hexagons are 6 sided polygons. They are found all over nature in honeycombs, snowflakes, basalt, turtles, and crystals.

Nonagons are 9 sided polygons. They can be used to draw a K9 complete graph and they also have no constructible way to be drawn with a compass and straightedge. They can also be used to represented the relationship between numbers in a magic square.
A decagon is a 10 sided polygon having all sides of equal length.
A dodecagon is a 12 sided polygon having all sides of equal length. Kurschak ( Hungarian Mathematician) states that a regular dodecagon inscribed in a unit circle has area 3.
An n-gon is a generalized polygon, a polygon with n sides.
A rectangular prism is a 3D solid with 6 rectangular sides.

A sphere in is a 3D surface where all points are distance R from the center point. The points of a line through the center of the sphere that intersect the sphere are called antipodal points. A great circle is a circle on the sphere that has the same radius of the sphere.

A cylinder is a basic geometric shape formed by the points at distance r from the straight line or the axis of the cylinder. A surface formed by two planes perpendicular to the axis at distance h apart are typically called cylinders.

A cone is a smooth surface that tapers from a base to a vertex. The base maybe any shape. If the base is square then it is a pyramid. If the base is circular and the axis passe through the center of the circular base then it is a right circular cone.
A frustum of a cone is a shape constructed by a plane parallel to the base of the cone cutting through the cone.
A regular pyramid is one whose base is a regular polygon with lateral edges all of equal length.
An elliptical paraboloid is a surface of revolution that opens upward. The revolution occurs about its axis and is used in mirrors, antenna, and reflectors such as those in some solar cells.
The monkey saddle is a surface that gets its name from the fact that a monkey should be able to straddle the shape and have a place to rest its tail.
The hyperbolic paraboloid is often called a saddle. This should not be confused with saddle points where are points on a surface such that the surface resembles a saddle at that point.
A quadric surface that can either be one or two sheets. A hyperboloid can be formed by revolving a hyperbola around its semi-minor axis.
A double cone are two cones placed apex to apex. By taking a plane and intersecting this surface we can create all the conical section shapes.
An ellipsoid is a quadratic surface. If two of the axes lengths are the same then the result is a spheroid, and if all three same then the result is a sphere.
A torus is a surface of revolution where a circle is revolved around a point in a coplanar circular way.

Ford-Fulkerson is very simple conceptually, if there's a path from the source to the sink with available capacity take it. Be aware though that there is no guarantee that the algorithm will terminate. A flow network can be created such that the flow doesn't converge to the maximum flow.
Insertion sort is one of the simplest sorting algorithms and if you've ever played cards you've probably done it in your head. The way most people sort cards is similar to the insertion sort method.
Heapsort is an in-place, unstable, selection sort. It's an O(n log n) sort, though on most machine a good implementation of quicksort will our perform it.

Quicksort is one of the most famous sorting algorithms. On average is is O(n log n), mainly due to the fat that its inner loop and be efficiently implemented on most architectures. Not only that, but it has rather good memory hierarchy usage by taking advantage or available caches. Also, since its an in-place search it requires no temporary memory.

Counting sort takes advantage of knowing the range of numbers in the array to be sorted, similar to bucket sort. The biggest limitation to counting sort is that it assumes that each of the elements is an integer in the range, or at least a comparator is used that makes the sorting done only to integers.
Merge sort is also an O(n log n) sorting algorithm. It is comparison based, stable and based on the divide and conquer paradigm.

Bucket sort works by partitioning an array into a given number of buckets or bins and either recursively running bucket sort on them or by using another search algorithm on the buckets. It is a distribution sort similar to radix sort, in fact top down radix can be seen as a special case of bucket sort. Also, if only two buckets are used then this becomes quicksort where the pivot value is always selected to be in the middle value range.

The longest common subsequence problem as an important application in both edit distance and genetic sequencing. With respect to edit distance, this problem is similar to helping your spell checker work properly. And in DNA sequencing were we have random permutations of A, C, G and T, this algorithm helps us find how common strands of DNA may be.

There are more applications for FFTs than we can list here. It is used in MRI (Magnetic resonance imaging) and in DSP (digital sound processing) as well as in many other time series analysis applications. Having an algorithm that computes the FFT rather quickly is great as long as you can assure that the input data is a power of 2. The thing to be aware of here is that you must be sure to reverse the bits or the whole thing is going to fail.

Simply put, computing the convex hull of a finite set of points in the place with O(n log n) is sweet. This is a very common algorithm in the video game industry whether for physics or path finding. If you work with vertices, or you can model your data with them then this is a good algorithm to have in your tool belt.

NPV is an indicator of how an investment or project performs for a firm. If a project is risky, but has a positive NPV you could think about accepting it. If you have multiple mutually exclusive alternatives, the one with the higher NPV should be selected. If the NPV > 0, the investment adds to the firms value. NPV < 0 subtracts value and if NPV = 0 the value added or subtracted is indifferent.
